{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_roseheath_ver01/data/sn92070146/00414188849/1937120101/0116.xml":{"full_text":"i\u00df\u00dfnvanvo\nALL TOT KIWI\nto mmuju\nWALLET\nWhere Teamwork\nCan Do the Job\nIndustry, labor and political econom\nists will find reason fox more than a\nfew hearty cheers in the message to\ncongress delivered by President Roose\nvelt on the subject of the construction\nindustry. Industry can cheer because the\ngoal set up by the president one that\nmeans a healthy renewal of activity,\nlabor can cheer because it means more\njobs, and political economists can cheer\nbecause there is sound business sense in\nthe program outlined by the president.\nComing at a time when the federal\ngovernment finds it urgently necessary\nto slash expenditures and at the same\ntime encourage business to new activity,\nthe housing program is particularly wel\ncome. It represents, the type of thing\nthe government can do to help both\nlabor and industry, without unduly pen\nalizing either. It does not provide for\nfederal extravagance in any project\nwhere money spent is money wasted.\nThe money government puts into this\nprogram, as in the National Housing\nprogram in the last two years, will be\namply insured. It represents investment,\nnot expenditure.\nBusiness, distrustful of the New Deal\nin many things, would only be harming\nitself if it did not go more than half\nway to make this proposed new, greater\nhousing program a success. And the pro\ngram cannot be a success without the\ncooperation of industry.\nThe president is right when he says,\n\u201cthe problem of reducing costs to a\npoint where larger volume, longer em\nployment and higher annual earnings\nare possible is one that must be solved\nin major part bv the building industry\nitself.\u201d\nThat very sentence indicates that the\nnation\u2019s chief executive has realized\nthat government cannot force recovery\nall by itself. Taken in conjunction with\nthe financing and low interest plans\noutlined by Roosevelt in his message\nto congress, it means that the govern\nment is willing to cooperate with busi\ness in making the program a success\nif only business will cooperate with the\ngovernment.\nThere are few communities in the\nUnited States which do not need better\nhousing facilities. There are few which\nwill not receive them if this new pro\ngram is carried through\u2014and all that\nis needed to carry it through is team\nwork between business and government.\nJohn L. Lewis'\nPeculiar Psychology\nJohn L. Lewis, whose dreams of dic\ntatorship over labor are slipping as\nfast as an inexperienced ice skater,\nsoars to a new height of eloquent ab\nsurdity when he tells a conference of\nfurniture workers that congress is to\nblame for business recession because it\nhas not given sufficient thought to \u201chow\nAmericans can be given the right to\nwork.\u201d\nWhat Mr. Lewis has in mind seems\nto be this: a man would walk into a\nfactory, present a union card and say,\n\u201cI want to go to work.\u201d Then, whether\nthere wds a job or not, whether the fac\ntory was making or losing money, he\nwould go to work. The question would\ncease to be whether there were any jobs\nopen; it would become, \u201cdoes anybody\nwant a job?\u201d\nWe cannot help thinking that Mr.\nLewis and his friends would get farther\nby saying to industry, to congress and\nto the nation, \u201cWe want to help. We\nwant what is due us, but we do not want\nto hurt ourselves and others by getting\nit in the wrong way. Let\u2019s work this\nthing out together.\u201d\nOut Our Way\nNOW VOU'LL HAVE\nTO 60 WITHOUT\nA FOOT WARMER\nYOU KICKED IT\nOVER!\nr\nVOU HAD IT\nTURNED UP\nTOO HIGH\nIT BURNT\nME, ANP I\nJUMPED!\n\nto\n\u20acS\n\nm\nvjMimlL\nW.\n\nW\nTm\nW\nr 7\nWJL\nA\n2\n'm\n\u2019\"\u2022ill:./*;\nc\nm\n.1\n0=\n?//s\n33\n\nn-,\nOn\nu\n<r:\nTis\nm\n9\n**r.\nx\n\n1\ntj\no\nUv\u00ab\nx\nW\ni\n\nU A.V* 4\nOH. ,*ST a \u00abMiKiMM .me eorn thirty years too soon\nt m me. u m of i\nO' a/iluam;\nThoughts for the Day\nHe that hath two coats, let him impart to him that\nhath none; and he that hath meat, let him do like\nwise.\u2014Luke 3:11.\nNews Behind the News\nBillions for Armament\nWASHINGTON.\u2014A mythical two and a half\nbillion dollar armament program for the United\nStates next year is the subject of Washington's\nmost persistent recent rumor.\nThere are several versions of the tale, all of\nwhich insist that Roosevelt whispered to this\nman or that one that an armament boom was\nhis rabbit-in-the-hat for curing the present\nbusiness \u201crecession.\u201d\nThe facts are that the President is a \u201cbig\nnavy\" man, that he already has decided on a\npolicy of having an American navy second to\nnone, that he would like to build up the navy\nrapidly and probably would try to do just that\nif there were no deterring factors.\nBut he and like-minded men in the admin\nistration realize that the American people won\u2019t\nsupport a huge naval program unless they feel\nthere\u2019s imminent danger of war.\nAnd the immediate plans for a \u201cshot in the\narm\u201d for business are confined to proposals for\nstimulating a private housing boom.\nThe President himself doesn\u2019t believe there is\ngoing to be big war in Europe, at least not in\nthe near future. But he has urged Americans\nnot to imagine that the western hemisphere can\nescape in any worldwide conflagration\nMeanwhile, America can't afford to take\nchances, in his view\u2019, because nb one really can\ntell what\u2019s going to happen In the international\nfield. F.D.R. and many others here are im\npressed by the spectacle of England, who found\nherself insufficiently armed to keep the Fascist\npowers from shoving her around\nNazi and Fascist penetration into South\nAmerica, especially in Brazil, has given Roose\nvelt and Secretary Hull a real headache and\nenters into considerations as to naval building.\nAt the time of Roosevelt's Chicago speech\nit had been decided that this country ought to\ngo almost any distance In cooperation with Eng\nland and France to curb Japanese aggression in\nChina, short of war. This attitude has been\ntoned down considerably as a result, first, of an\nunenthusiastic reaction to the President\u2019s speech\nin this country, and. second, discovery at Brus\nsels that Britain felt in a conciliatory mood\ntoward Japan.\nThe British position is still the key to the\ninternational situation and British unwillingness\nto act sternly anywhere should have been no\nsurprise to the State Department.\nWord was quietly conveyed to the State De\npartment long ago that his majesty\u2019s govern\nment would try to take no strong role on the\ninternational stage until it felt rearmament had\nreached the point where England could \u201cclear\nup the Mediterranean situation,\u201d a situation\nwhich involves Italian machinations in Egypt,\nPalestine, Arabia and other Mediterranean areas.\nBritish attitude, as understood here, has been\nthat England could placate Hitler and either\nbeat or frighten Mussolini into subordination.\nHow this idea will really work out or what may\nhappen in the meantime is anybody's guess.\nA large group of other uncertainties have\ncombined to make Roosevelt\u2019s big navy, be\nready-for-anything attitude increasingly more\npopular in Washington.\nOther Editors Say\nCONSUMERS\u2019 COOPERATIVES\n(Underwriters\u2019 Report)\nIn discussing \u201cConsumers\u2019 Co-operatives\u201d be\nfore the Dallas convention of the National\nAssociation of Insurance Agents, Bert E. Mitcher\nof Hutchinson, Kansas, said in part:\nWe are fighting for vastly more than our own\nbusiness. We are fighting for the continuance\nof the American way of doing business. Any\nsort of collectivism eventually eliminates the\nindividual. Under the promise of a more abun\ndant life or an easier way, the individual surren\nders his freedom. He becomes a part of the\ngroup. He loses his identity and individual rights.\nBecause he is a part of the group he must act\nwith the group and be subject to orders from\nleaders of the group. More and more he is told\nwhat to do and when to do it. Gradually he is\nmore and more dependent on the group. In\nthis state he is regimented in his thinking, his\nhabits and his living Individuality and freedom\nhave vanished.\nWhat of the Heritage we shall leave? Will it\nbe an insipid, colorless, regimented, unidentified\nplace in a collective society or a chance to con\ntinue the building of a better civilization, a\nbetter standard of living, a place where homes\nare held in high esteem and where religion is\nfostered and respected?\nNoting that auto shows are featuring\ncars cut in two, a friend, who did\u2019nt see\nthe other driver coming, is interested in\nselling his for display.\nMontana now has a trailer classroom.\nIt is a way of keeping up with the geo\ngraphy during a dust storm.\nby Williams\nEditorials and Comment\nNew York Day by Day\nNEW YORK. Dec. 1 The great-)\nmansions along Fifth and Park\navenues* fabled Gold Coast have\nwhat they call \u201cservants halls\u201d\ninstead of thel\nlowly term ofl\n\u2022employees' quar-l\nters. Indeed, a|\nnumber are al-|\nmost baronial in|\ntheir appoint-j\nments, even tol\nroof patios with!\nfountains. I\nIn the big re-|\nsidences the ser\nvants\u2019 hall is al\nmost a separate'\n(e.s t a b I i shmenti\nAside from sunny individual rooms,\nthere is a rest room with comfort\nable divans and chairs. And there\nis a library and music room where\nthe radio and late phonograph re\ncords may be heard.\nAll is made so pleasant that\nmany of the servants do not care\nto leave, even on their evenings\noff. There is one imposing castle\nnorth of the 90's on Park that not\nonly has its own dining room but\nalso separate cook and waitresses\nwho serve the help.\nWith the growing reluctance of\nmany to enter domestic service,\nnew homes are making especial\ngestures toward servant comfort.\nThere is very little in the way of\nliving ease denied. Indeed as things\nare. such servants have fewer wor\nries than employers.\nAdolphe Menjou surprised his\nNew York friends recently by his\nphysical appearence. For a time he\nlooked as though he might be play\ning hookey from a graveyard. As\nthe result of a stomach malady he\nhad become shriveled, sallow and\nwan. So much so that only the art\nof the makeup made it possible\nfor him to be screened. About a\nyear ago he underwent an abdomi\nnal operation which was successful.\nSince he has taken on 30 pounds in\nweight, the bloom has returned to\nhis cheeks, his eyes are bright and\nsparkling and is step has the dash\nof the cavalier roles he so often\nportrays. For several years he lived\non bran, graham crackers and sips\nof tepid water. Today he can tear\ninto a five-inch steak with trim\nmings and do right well by it.\nGertrude Lawrence is one of the\n\u201chello everybody\u201d girls of the\ncafes, too. When she enters a place\nstrangers are likely to get a warm\ngreeting, for she takes no chances\non an astigmatism causing offense.\nWithout glasses most faces a few\nsteps away are a bit blurry, so she\nbows to all. Fifi Widenes Wich\nleld is another completely lost\nwithout her lorgnette. Unless she\nhas it in use she can walk into\na room filled with friends and not\nrecognize a soul. A most demo\ncratic lady, for years she was, un\ntil her affliction became known,\nregarded as a snob. The captivat\ning Betty Starbuck is one of the\nblind-without-glasses girls who has\nhad to do a lot of explaining to\nkeep some of her friends she pas\nsed without even a glance of reco\ngnition. But perhaps the worst\nvictim of all is Libby Holman. She,\nLEGAL ADVERTISEMENT\nSUMMONS\nNo. 17748\nIN THE SUPERIOR COURT OP\nTHE STAE OF CALIFORNIA, IN\nAND FOR THE COUNTY OF\nIMPERIAL.\nIMPERIAL IRRIGATION\nDISTRICT Plaintiff\nvs.\nGEORGE E. TUTTLE, et al..\nDefendants.\nHarry W. Horton Geo. R. Kirk,\nAttorneys for Plaintiff.\nTHE PEOPLE OF THE STATE\nOF CALIFORNIA SEND GREET\nINGS TO: GEORGE E. TUTTLE,\nHELEN FINUCANE. TITLE GUAR\nANTEE and TRUST COMPANY, a\nCorporation. Trustee. F. E. ELLIS,\nCITIZENS NATIONAL TRUST\nSAVINGS BANK OF LOS AN\nGELES, a national banking asso\nciation. Trustee, JOHN BONDY,\nH. WATAMURA, WESTERN VEG\nETABLE DISTRIBUTORS, a Cor\nporation, JOHN DOE, JANE DOE,\nRICHARD ROE, JOHN DOE COM.\nPANY. a Corporation, and RICH\nARD ROE COMPANY, a Co-part\nnership, Defendants.\nYOU ARE HEREBY DIRECTED\nTO APPEAR and answer the Com\nplaint in an action entitled as above,\nbrought against you in the Superior\nCourt of the County of Imperial,\nState of California, within ten days\nafter the service on you of this\nSummons if served within this\ncounty; or within thirty -days if\nserved elsewhere.\nAnd you are hereby notified that\nunless you appear and answer as\nabove required, the said plaintiff\nwill take judgment for any money\nor damages demanded in the com\nplaint, as arising upon contract, or\nit will apply to the Court for any\nother relief demanded in the Com\nplaint.\nGiven under my hand and the\nseal of the Superior Court of the\nCounty of Imperial, State of Cali\nfornia, this 6th day of July, 1937.\nw. j. McClelland,\n(SEAL) County Clerk\nBy G. O. KENYON,\nDeputy Clerk.\nS 29 O 6 13 20 27 N 3 10 17 24 D 1.\nSUMMONS\nNo. 17733\nIN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF\nTHE STATE OP CALIFORNIA\nIN AND FOR THE COUNTY OF\nIMPERIAL.\nIMPERIAL IRRIGATION\nDISTRICT, Plaintiff\nvs.\nE. M. PEASE, et al\u201e\nDefendants.\nHarry W. Horton and Geo. R.\nKirk. Attorneys for Plaintiff.\nTHE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF\nCALIFORNIA SEND GREETINGS\nTO:\nE. M. PEASE, THE FIRST NA\nTIONAL BANK OF POMONA, a\nWEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 1, 1937\nto. O. Mclntyre\nincidentally, was first, according\nto an optical journal, to wear\nglasses that fitted over the eye\nballs.\nI've frequenly wondered what\nManhattan maid is the greatest\nheadturner when entering a cafe.\nAs a rule it is the one most publi\ncized. For a long time Peggy Joyce\n\u2014and where is she now?\u2014stopped\nthe buzzing and pivoted everybody\nin chairs when she swept in. Lib\nby Holman, too, had her day. But\nof late Elsa Maxwell appears to\nbe the top head-turner. She Is\neasily recognized because of her\nbouncing figure and gait and the\nfact that she never indulges for\nmal evening dress. Incidentally,\nMiss Maxwell has added lustre to\nher versatility in a writing role.\nEditors say her biography in Har\nper\u2019s Bazaar is the wittest scrib-\nYou re Telling Me\nBY WILLIAM KITT\nWARNING TO ALL young bride\ngrooms: Make certain now that\nyour bride will not, in the future,\nwonder whether the name \u201cspouse\u201d\nshouldn't be correctly pronounced\n\"souse\u201d.\nIt must be distinctly unsetting\nto the American who becomes\nquickly wrathful over the way the\nItalians are treating the Ethio\npians and the Japanese the Chin\nese to suddenly realize that he\nnever sees\u2014never has seen!\u2014\nIndians on Main street!\nZadok Dumbkopf has just come\nin with what he thinks Is the\neighth wonder of the world. It\u2019s\nthis: \"Why do the Japanese con\ntinue to issue statements that their\ninentions are entirely peaceable\nwhen no one, no even Japanese,\nbelieve them?\u201d\nGlass windshields, according to\na news item, are now being made\nof coal in Great Britain. When\nthe London fog arrive it probably\ndoesn\u2019t make any difference what\nthey are made of.\nBarbs\nWHILE everyone else considers\nU. S. gold safe in its Kentucky\ntomb, budget skeptics won't be sat\nisfied until someone puts a good,\nstiff curse on it.\nRussians refuse to explain thleir\nsolution to the puzzle of the Polar\nDrift, probably because it gets so\nfar off the Party line.\nThe gargler who imitates a wa\nterfall for the radio is getting the\nrazz from his wife. She says he\ntalks shop last thing before bed\nand first thing in the morning.\nAfter the court change proposal,\nRoosevelt\u2019s chart showed a sharp\ndip. That was when the ship of\nsate was taking the popularity\ncurve on two wheels.\nLEGAL ADVERTISEMENT\nCorporation, a National Banking\nAssociation, ELMER L. HENDER\nSON, CLARK HORSFORD. JEAN\nSMITH FJERESTAD, CHAS. R.\nSTEAD, HUBERT LEBUS, H. C.\nCLARK. JOHN DOE, JANE DOE,\nRICHARD ROE, JOHN DOE COM\nPANY, a Corporation, and RICH\nARD ROE COMPANY, a Co-part\nnership, Defendants.\nYou Are Hereby Directed to Ap\npear and answer the Complaint in\nan action entitled as above, brought\nagainst you in the Superior Court\nof the County of Imperial, State of\nCalifornia, within ten days after\nthe service on you of this Summons\n\u2014if served within this county; or\nwithin thirty days if served else\nwhere.\nAnd you are hereby notified that\nunless you appear and answer as\nabove required, the said plaintiff\nwill take judgment for any money\nor damages demanded in the com\nplaint, as arising upon contract, or\nit will apply to the Court for any\nother relief demanded in the Com\nplaint.\nGiven under my hand and the\nseal of the Superior Court of the\nCounty of Imperial, State of Cali\nfornia, this 30th day of June, 1937.\nW. J. MCCLELLAND,\n(SEAL) County Clerk\nBy G. O. KENYON,\nNOTICE OF SALE OF PROPERTY\nTO SATISFY LIEN OF KEEPER\nOF HOTEL. INN, OR FUR\nNISHED APARTMENT\nHOUSE FOR GUESTS\nCHARGES\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN\nthat Allied Properties, a hotel, inn\nand furnished apartment house\nkeeper, will on the 10th day of\nDecember, 1937, at the hour of 10\no\u2019clock AM., at the American Stor\nage Building, 3636 Beverly Boule\nvard, in the City of Los Angeles.\nCounty of Los Angeles, State of\nCalifornia, sell at public auction to\nthe highest bidder, the following\nlots of baggage and other property,\nto satisfy charges due from tenants\nor guests and for costs.\nThe names of the debtors, the\namount due from each and a brief\ndescription of the property to be\nsold is as follows:\nLot No. I\u2014Mrs. Henry Busse,\n$27.60, one bag, contents unknown;\nLot No. 2\u2014J. A. Hennessey, $36.19,\none Gladstone bag, contents un\nknown;\nLot No. 3\u2014Captain C. A. Mc\u00dfride,\n$44.40, one suit case, contents un\nknown; i\nLot No. 4\u2014Ruth Steward, $38.35,\none suitcase, contents unknown.\nDATED: Nov. 9, 1937.\nCOL. E. C. JENKINS.\nLicensed Auctioneer.\nALLIED PROPERTIES\nBy B. H. DORR,\nOffice Manager.\nN 10 17 24, D 1.\nBy 0. 0. Mclntyre\nbling effort of our time.\nWalter Chrysler\u2019s son-in-law,\nByron Foy, only a few years re\nmoved from the Texas farm, has\nbecome one of the town\u2019s polished\nmen of affairs. Those who know\nsay that although he worked for\nhis wife\u2019s father he started from\nscratch\u2014 and has been entirely on\nhis own, winning a top post solely\nby hard work and good judgment.\nAnd in white tie and tails in the\nboxes at the Horse Show and Met\nropolitan. he suggests one of Noel\nCoward's super-sophisticates.\nOne of the friendly idiots who\nsneak up behind a fellow, tweak\nhis leg and then bark like a dog\nwas loose near Grand Central to\nday and worked out on me. I tried\nto laugh it off in the upper regis\nter, ha. ha, but I had to go to a\nphone, booth and phone the house\nto,see what they sent me out for.\nFactographs\nStreet car funeral parades are a\ncommon sight on street of Mex\nico City. Relatives of the deceased\nrent highly decorated open cars for\nthe corpse, and follow-up cars for\nthe mourners.\nLord Nuffield, the \u201cHenry Ford\nof Great Britain\u2019*, has given a to\ntal of $37,000,000 to Oxford uni\nversity. His fortune was made\nthrough manufacture of small\nautomobiles.\nThe United States uses an aver\nage of 10.000.000 tons of paper per\nyear. This is more than the re\nmainder of the world consumes.\nWebster\u2019s dictionary was once\nbarred from Arkansas because its\ndefinition of \u201cevolution\" was ob\njectionable to fundamentalists.\nThe Grab Bag\nOne-Minute Test\n1. Who is premier of France?\n2. What is the minimum age for\nthe U. S. presidency?\n3. What city is capital of Can\nada?\nHints on Etiquette\nA woman should not wear a for\nmal evening dress to the theater\nwhen accompanied by a man wear\ning ordinary street clothes.\nWords of Wisdom\nOne may smile and smile and\nsmile and be a villain still. \u2014Shake-\nspeare.\nToday\u2019s Horoscope\nMany persons whose birthday oc\ncurs today have abundant self\nconfidence. They win positions of\nleadership through their positive\nnature.\nOne-Minute Test Answers\n1 Camille Chautemps, a Radi\ncal-Socialist.\n2. The U. S. constitution sets a\nminimum age of 35 years for the\npresidency.\nLEGAL ADVERTISEMENT\nIN AND FOR THE COUNTY OF\nIMPERIAL.\nIMPERIAL IRRIGATION\nDISTRICT, Plaintiff\nvs.\nR. B. WOOD, SECURITY TITLE\nINSURANCE AND GUARANTEE\nCOMPANY, a Corporation, Trustee,\nJ. L. HENNING. ERLE GANS, Trus\ntee. W. G. MOORE, Trustee. BANK\nOF TEHAMA COUNTY, a Banking\nCorporation, et al.,\nDefendants.\nHarry W. Horton and Geo. R.\nKirk, Attorneys for Plaintiff.\nTHE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF\nCALIFORNIA SEND GREETINGS\nTO:\nR. B. WOOD, SECURITY TITLE\nINSURANCE AND GUARANTEE\nCOMPANY, a Corporation. Trustee,\nJ. L. HENNING, ERLE GANS,\nTrustee, W. G. MOORE. Trustee.\nBANK OF TEHAMA COUNTY, a\nBanking Corporation. JOHN DOE.\nJANE DOE. RICHARD ROE. JOHN\nDOE COMPANY, and RICHARD\nROE COMPANY, a Co-partnership,\nDefendants.\nYou Arp Hereby Directed to Ap\npear and answer the Complaint in\nan action entitled as above, brought\nagainst you in the Superior Court\nof the County of Imperial, State\nof California, within ten days after\nthe service on you of this Alias Sum\nmons\u2014if served within this county:\nor within thirty days if served else\nwhere.\nAnd you are hereby notified that\nunless you appear and answer as\nabove required, the said plaintiff\nwill take judgment for any money\nor damages demanded in the com\nplaint. as arising upon contract, or\nit will apply to the Court for any\nother relief demanded in the Com\nplaint.\nGiven under my hand and the\nseal of the Superior Court of the\nCounty of Imperial, State of Cali\nfornia. this 2nd day of September,\n1937.\nw. j. McClelland,\n(SEAL) County Clerk.\nBy G. O. KENYON,\nDeputy Clerk.\nO 6 13 20 37, N 3 10 17 24, D 1 8.\nSUMMONS\nNo. 17822\nIN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF\nTHE STATE OF CALIFORNIA\nIN AND FOR THE COUNTY OF\nIMPERIAL.\nIMPERIAL IRRIGATION\nDISTRICT, Plaintiff\nvs.\nJAMES L. LOMBARD, TRUSTEE,\net al\u201e Defendants.\nHarry W. Horton and Geo. R.\nKirk, Attorneys for Plaintiff.\nTHE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF\nCALIFORNIA SEND GREETINGS\nTO\nJAMES L. LOMBARD, Trustee,\nHENRY C. KENNAH, WILLIAM\nFamous Sayings\nGive what you have. To some it may be better than\nyou dare to think\u2014Longfellow.\nBruce Catton Says:\nPeople Should Have Last Word on War\nDivided on almost everything\nelse, members of the present Con\ngress seem to be agreed on one\nthing: that above everything else\nthe American people want to stay\nout of any and all wars that may\ncome over the horizon.\nIn this congressmen undoubtedly\nreflect the wishes of their consti\ntuents. No one can doubt that\nthe people of this country want\npeace. War may start overnight in\nalmost any part of the world; if\npublic sentiment means anything,\nthis country will stay out if it be\nhumanly possible.\nBut the peace-loving people of\nthe United States might as well\nunderstand one thing. Under ex\nisting laws, they can be taken into\nwar against their own will, and\nthey can do nothing about it but\ntake it and like it.\nIn the first place, any President\ncan, if he wishes, maneuver the\ncountry into a spot where war be\ncomes practically inevitable. Wil\nson did it, unintentionally, in the\nWorld War; any succeeding Presi\ndent could do the same.\nIn the second place, it is Con\ngress that declares war. Susceptible\nto pressure of all kinds, Congress\nmight conceivalby declare war\nwhen a majority of the people did\nnot want war. It is still an open\nquestion, for instance, whether a\nmajority of Americans wanted to\nThe American moose, largest\nmember of the deer family, reaches\na height of 84 inches at the shoul\nders.\nSeveral Detroit auto manufac\nturers are experimenting with rub\nber seat springs.\nAuction Philosophy\nBy D. L ZINN\nFolks, if any of you get a bad case of appendicitis\nand can\u2019t get hold of a doctor, just call me. I have seen\nso many of these operations during the past two years\nI think I could take one out in a pinch. I had to take\nRex, our youngest boy, to the hospital yesterday for\none of those appendicitis operations. Somebody else is\ngoing to have to furnish most of \u2019em from now on\nin that kind of case, for we are about to run out of ap\npendixes. But I suppose it\u2019s like these new fangled\ntaxes, about the time you think you have \u2019em all\nstraightened up a new one jumps up and hits you right\nbetween the eyes.\nEl Centro Merchants baseball team beat the great\nMr. Moss, one of the best colored pitchers in the United\nStates next to Sachel Paige. These boys are sure play\ning that old baseball game. Next Sunday El Centro\nwill see one of the DiMaggio boys from San Fran\u00abisco\nin action with the Farley baseball team. Our team is\nlike old Bob Fitsimmons. He used to say \u201cthe bigger\nthey are, the harder they fall, so let \u2019em come.\nRoosevelt has gone fishing and I think congress has\ngone holiday shopping. We will see in a few .days. We\nknow now how they acted last time he went fishing.\nIt always makes the help sore when the boss goes fish\ning and leaves them a lot of work to do. I don\u2019t blame\n\u2019em. I\u2019ll be seein\u2019 you.\nLEGAL ADVERTISEMENT LEGAL ADVERTISEMENT\nS. WORDEN, BERTHA E. WOR\nDEN, ARTHUR BRYANT, MARY\nL. VICKREY, BELA TAYLOR, T. S.\nTAYLOR, G. PINADO, MARY M.\nKUNZ, MAUD KUNZ, SANTA FE\nLAND COMPANY, a Corporation,\nW H. SPAKE, RUTH PECK, A. C.\nSABIN, LOMBARD and SON, In\ncorporated, JOHN DOE, JANE DOE,\nRICHARD ROE, JOHN DOE COM\nPANY, a Corporation, and RICH\nARD ROE COMPANY, a Co\npartnership, Defendants.\nYou Are Directed to Appear and\nanswer the Complaint in an action\nentitled as above, brought against\nyou in the Superior Court of the\nCounty of Imperial, State of Cali\nfornia, within ten days after the\nservice on you of this Summons\u2014if\nserved within this county; or within\nthirty days if served elsewhere.\nAnd you are hereby notified that\nunless you appear and answer as\nabove required, the said plaintiff\nwill take judgment for any money\nor damages demanded in the com\nplaint. as arising upon contract, or\nit will apply to the Court for any\nother relief demanded in the Com\nplaint.\nGiven under my hand and the\nseal of the Superior Court of the\nCounty of Imperial, State of Cali\nfornia, this 31st day of August, 1937.\nw. j. McClelland,\nfSEAL) County Clerk.\nBy CITHA LAMSON.\nDeputy Clerk.\nO C 13 20 37, N 3 10 17 24, D 1 8.\nCERTIFICATE OF DOING BUSI\nNESS UNDER FICTITIOUS\nNAME\nNOTICE is hereby given that the\nundersigned Gene Higgins is tran\nsacting business in the City of El\nCentro, County of Imperial, State\nof California under the name of\nGolden Valley Dairy.\nThat his full name and place of\nresidence is as follows:\nGene Higgins, two miles West of\nthe City Limits of El Centro on the\nSan Diego Highway; Route 2, Box\n198, El Centro, California.\nGENE HIGGINS.\nSTATE OF CALIFORNIA\nCOUNTY OF IMPERIAL ss.\nOn this 9th day of November, 1937,\nbefore me, L. Lee Nuffer, a Notary\nPublic in and for the County of\nImperial, State of California, per\nsonally appeared Gene Higgins,\nknown to me to be the person whose\nname is subscribed to the within\nInstrument and acknowledged to me\nthat he executed the same.\nIN WITNESS WHEREOF, I have\nhereunto set my hand and affixed\nmy official seal the day and year\nin this certificate first above\nwritten.\nL. LEE NUFFER,\nNotary Public in and for said\nState and County.\n(Notarial Seal)\nN 10 17 24, D 1\ngo to war with Germany in the\nspring of 1917.\nThere are now pending in the\nSenate two bills which air to\nremedy this situation. Introduced\nby Senator LaFollette of Wisconsin\nand Senator Capper of Kansas,\nthese bills call for a constitutional\namendment which would put any\ndeclaration of war up to a nation\nwide referendum for ratification.\nUnless a majority of the people\nvoted for war, war could not be\ndeclared.\nThe only exception would be in\ncase of invasion by a foreign pow\ner of the United States or any\nother North American nation\n\u201cEvery man in the nation will\njump to arms in case the United\nStates is invaded or threatened\nwith invasion,\u2019\u2019 says Senator Cap\nper. \u201cBut when it comes to war\noverseas, the American people be\nlieve they have the right to pass\non their participation in such\nwars, and I agree.\u201d\nAnd says Senator LaFollette;\n\u201cI believe that if the American\npeople are competent to elect con\ngressmen and senators to make\nsuch a tremendous decision, they\nare equally competent to arrive at\nthe decision themselves.\u2019\u2019\nIt is pretty hard to find any\nflaws in that sort of logic. fl\nEarly action on one or the othei v\nof these two bills would be ad\nvisable. The danger of a new\nw\u2019orld war sees to be getting great\ner all the time. Here is one safe\nguard to which the American peo\nple are entitled \u2014the right to say\nfor themselves whether they shall\nsend armies to fight overseas. The\nmachinery to give them that right\nmight as well be put in motion at\nonce.\nNOTICE OF TRUSTEE\u2019S SALE\nNo. 50977\nWHEREAS. James A. Ross and\nAda Ross, husband and wife, by\nDeed of Trust dated November 25,\n1929, and recorded December 5,\n1929, in Book 256 of Official Rec\nords of Impgrial County, California,\nat Page 13, et seq., did grant and\nconvey that certain real property\nhereinafter described, to SECURITY'\nTITLE INSURANCE AND GUAR\nANTEE COMPANY, a corporation,\nas Trustee, to secure, among other\nthings, One promissory note in the\naggregate sum of Six Hundred and\nno-100 ($600.00) Dollars, with in\nterest thereon at the rate of Eight\nper cent per annum, payable semi\nannually in favor of Frank B.\nHoltzclaw, and duly assigned to\nF. M. Hunter and Bessie Hunter,\nhis wife, as Joint Tenants, by As\nsignment dated April 4, 1935. and\nrecorded April 13, 1935, in Book 401,\npage 187 of Official Records of Im\nperial county; also to secure any\nother sums of money which might\nbecome due and payable under the\nterms of said Deed of Trust: and,\nWHEREAS, Default was made in\nthe payments due upon said note\nand obligation, in that the follow\ning items were not paid when due,\nand still remain due, owing\nunpaid: V\nInstallment of Principal due\nApril 1, 1935, and all subsequent\ninstallments of principal, to\ngether with interest from April\n1, 1935; and,\nWHEREAS. In accordance with\nthe provisions of said note and\nDeed of Trust, and by reason of\nsuch default, the owner and holder\nof said note, and obligations exer\ncised the option given therein and\ndid declare all sums secured thereby\nto be immediately due and payable,\nand did execute and deliver to the\nTrustee a written declaration of\ndefault and demand for sale, and\nthereafter, in accordance with the\nprovisions of Section 2924 of the\nCivic Code, did record a notice of\ndefault and breach in the condi\ntions of said Deed of Trust, which\nsaid notice was recorded March 9,\n1937, in Book 451 of the Official\nRecords of Imperial County, Cali\nfornia, at Page 356 et seq.; and,\nWHEREAS. Said Deed of Trust\nprovides that after three months\nshall have elapsed following such\nrecordation of said notice, the\nTrustee, without demand, shall sell\nsaid property as therein provided;\nNOW THEREFORE, Notice is\nhereby given that by virtue of the\nauthority vested under said Deed\nof Trust, said Security Title In\nsurance and Guarantee Company\nwill sell at public auction to the, -i\nhighest bidder for cash in lawful\n(Continued on Page 9; Col. 1)","height":"29548","width":"23196"}}
